  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at preventing money laundering:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) sets global standards for combating money laundering and terrorist financing.\n\n2. The United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime provides guidelines for member states to combat money laundering.\n\n3. The Palermo Convention (2000) requires signatories to criminalize money laundering and establish regulatory frameworks.\n\n4. The Basel Committee on Banking Supervision provides recommendations for banks to prevent money laundering.\n\n5. Many countries have implemented domestic laws like the U.S. Bank Secrecy Act and anti-money laundering (AML) regulations.\n\nThese frameworks typically require financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n- Conduct due diligence on international transactions\n\nPenalties for money laundering can include significant fines and criminal prosecution.",
